\subsection{Ideal of a ring}
\begin{definition}\label{ring.ideal}
\uses{group.subgroup,ring}
If $R$ is a {{KNOWL('ring', 'ring')}}, a subset $I\subseteq R$ is an **ideal** of $R$ if $I$ is a {{KNOWL('group.subgroup', 'subgroup')}} of $R$ for $+$ and for all $a\in I$ and all $r\in R$,
$$ r\cdot a\in I \qquad\text{and}\qquad a\cdot r\in I.$$

In a polynomial ring $R[X_1,\dots,X_n]$, an ideal is **homogeneous** if it can be generated by homogeneous polynomials.

\end{definition}


